<exercise number="55"><statement><p><ol>
    <li><p>Is it true that <m>(x + y)^{-2} = x^{-2} + y^{-2}</m>? Explain why or why not.</p></li>
    <li><p>Give a numerical example to support your answer.</p></li>
</ol></p></statement>
<answer><p><ol>
    <li><p>No, because <m>\frac{1}{(x+y)^2}</m> is not <m>\frac{1}{x^2} + \frac{1}{y^2}</m>.</p></li>
    <li><p>Let <m>x = 1</m>, <m>y = 2</m>, then <m>(x + y)^{-2} = (1 + 2)^{-2} = 3^{-2} = \frac{1}{9}</m>, but <m>x^{-2} + y^{-2} = 1^{-2} + 2^{-2} = 1 + \frac{1}{4} = \frac{5}{4}</m> </p></li>
</ol></p></answer>
</exercise>

